# deploy/docker/crontab — the pipeline schedule inside a node, run by
# supercronic (the scheduler service). Five-field cron format; the shell that
# runs each command inherits this container's environment, so $LOGDIR below is
# the one set here.
#
# It replaces the laptop crontab's pipeline lines and nothing else: the
# personal update-main-branches.sh entry is deliberately absent, because it
# refreshes the owner's interactive checkouts and a node has none — the cycles
# clone their targets fresh from GitHub every time.
#
# The redirections match the laptop's so the dashboard's log-derived views
# keep working: cron.log and review-cron.log live in state_dir and are read
# back by scripts/publish-dashboard.sh.
#
# Whether the cycle lines do anything at all is decided by AGENT_OPS_ROLE
# (requirement 2.4): on a standby node each one writes a single line to its log
# and exits. The schedule is therefore identical on every node, and failing
# over is a matter of changing one variable, not editing this file.

LOGDIR=/home/agent/.local/state/poetic-agents

*/5 * * * *  /app/scripts/publish-dashboard-launcher.sh
0   * * * *  /app/agent-cycle.sh  >> $LOGDIR/cron.log        2>&1
29  3 * * *  /app/review-cycle.sh >> $LOGDIR/review-cron.log 2>&1

# The fleet's shared memory, both directions, on every node. The push
# publishes this node's state as its own `nodes/<NODE_NAME>` branch — on an
# active node that is its cycles, on a standby it is the heartbeat that tells
# the fleet dashboard a spare is alive. The fetch materialises every peer's
# branch for the union readers (blocked/void, the no-op fingerprint, the
# usage-limit cooldown, the fleet dashboard). Offset cadences so the two do
# not queue behind each other every single tick; the mirror lock arbitrates
# when they do coincide.
*/5 * * * *  /app/scripts/state-sync.sh push  >> $LOGDIR/state-sync.log 2>&1
*/7 * * * *  /app/scripts/state-sync.sh fetch >> $LOGDIR/state-sync.log 2>&1
